<section>
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <p>The Caring Place is a non-profit social service organization serving the needs of domestic violence and sexual assault victims, primarily in Lake, Porter, and Starke counties in Northwest Indiana. Founded in 1977 by volunteers in Hobart, we now operate from Valparaiso, offering shelter at no cost, community education, support groups, legal counseling, case management, and independent living planning.</p>

      <h2>Our mission</h2>
      <p>We provide inclusive service, shelter, and ongoing support for people experiencing domestic violence — and work to empower people to build supportive, respectful, compassionate relationships through advocacy and education.</p>

      <h2>Our vision</h2>
      <p>A community free from domestic violence, in which all people engage in healthy relationships, supported by a society committed to nurturing respect and non-violence.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <p style="font-family:var(--serif);font-size:20px;font-weight:600;color:var(--plum)">"Breaking the Silence that Hides the Violence."</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="services">
  <div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">Our History</p>
    <h2>Nearly 50 years of service</h2>
    <ul class="checklist" style="margin-top:32px;max-width:72ch">
      <li><strong>Mid-1970s</strong> — Citizens formed a task force studying domestic violence victim needs.</li>
      <li><strong>1978–1979</strong> — The Caring Place incorporated and opened its first shelter at the former St. Bridget's Church convent.</li>
      <li><strong>1986–1990</strong> — Moved to the Wheeler farmhouse and expanded services, then relocated to our current Valparaiso site with 24-bed capacity.</li>
      <li><strong>2002</strong> — Acquired a new Community Advocacy Center facility.</li>
      <li><strong>2018–2019</strong> — Broke ground on and opened the new Caring Place Center for Change, our current 12-bedroom shelter.</li>
      <li><strong>Today</strong> — A staff of 11 full-time and 7 part-time team members serve 125–150 shelter residents and 300–350 community clients each year.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
